****Health:
Significance of Health
1)Complete well-being:
Health means physical, mental, and social well-being ‚Äî not just absence of disease.

2)Efficient functioning:
A healthy person can work efficiently, study better, and perform daily tasks properly.

3)Strong immunity:
Good health helps the body to fight infections and recover quickly from illnesses.

4)Emotional stability:
Good health keeps the mind calm and stress-free, leading to better decision-making.

5)Social and economic importance:
Healthy people contribute more productively to society and reduce medical costs.

****Diff in healthy and desses free body:
| **S.No.** | **Healthy Person**                                         | **Disease-free Person**                                        |
| --------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| 1Ô∏è‚É£       | Means **complete physical, mental, and social well-being** | Means **no signs of disease** only                             |
| 2Ô∏è‚É£       | A person may be **disease-free but not healthy**           | A person can be disease-free but still **unhappy or stressed** |
| 3Ô∏è‚É£       | **Positive concept** ‚Äî includes happiness and fitness      | **Negative concept** ‚Äî only absence of illness                 |
| 4Ô∏è‚É£       | Depends on **lifestyle, nutrition, and environment**       | Depends only on **absence of infection or disorder**           |
| 5Ô∏è‚É£       | Example: A cheerful, active person with good relations     | Example: A weak, tired person without any disease              |

üåø Essential Conditions for Good Health
Balanced Diet
‚Äì Provides all necessary nutrients, vitamins, and minerals in correct proportion.
‚Äì Helps the body grow, repair, and stay energetic.
Clean Environment
‚Äì Pollution-free surroundings and clean water reduce risk of diseases.
‚Äì Proper sanitation and waste disposal are important.
Personal Hygiene
‚Äì Regular bathing, brushing, washing hands, and wearing clean clothes prevent infections.
Proper Rest and Exercise
‚Äì Physical activity keeps the body fit, and rest/sleep helps recovery and relaxation.

‚öïÔ∏è Disease and Its Causes
üîπ What is a Disease?
A disease is a condition in which normal functioning of the body is disturbed, leading to physical or mental discomfort.
It means ‚Äúnot at ease.‚Äù

**Causes of desese:
| **Type of Cause**                     | **Explanation**                                                             | **Examples**                                                           |
| ------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **1. Pathogenic (Infectious) agents** | Caused by **microorganisms** like bacteria, viruses, fungi, protozoa, worms | *Bacteria* ‚Äì Tuberculosis, *Virus* ‚Äì Common cold, *Protozoa* ‚Äì Malaria |
| **2. Nutritional causes**             | Due to **lack or excess** of nutrients in diet                              | Deficiency of Vitamin C ‚Äì *Scurvy*, Iron ‚Äì *Anemia*                    |
| **3. Genetic causes**                 | Caused by **defects in genes or chromosomes**                               | *Hemophilia*, *Down‚Äôs syndrome*                                        |
| **4. Environmental causes**           | Due to **pollution, poor sanitation, unsafe water, climate**                | Asthma, Skin infections                                                |
| **5. Lifestyle causes**               | Due to **habits like smoking, alcohol, junk food, stress**                  | Heart disease, Diabetes, Obesity                                       |


ü¶† Sources of Disease
üîπ Definition:
Sources of disease are the places or mediums from which disease-causing organisms (pathogens) enter a healthy person‚Äôs body.

***Main sources of desese:
| **Source**              | **Description**                                                          | **Examples of Diseases**                                 |
| ----------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------- |
| **1. Air**              | When pathogens spread through **air droplets** from coughing or sneezing | Common cold, Tuberculosis, COVID-19                      |
| **2. Water**            | When **contaminated water** carries pathogens                            | Cholera, Typhoid, Hepatitis A                            |
| **3. Food**             | **Spoiled or contaminated food** can spread microbes                     | Food poisoning, Diarrhea                                 |
| **4. Insects/Vectors**  | **Mosquitoes, flies, lice** act as carriers of pathogens                 | Malaria (mosquito), Plague (rat flea), Dengue (mosquito) |
| **5. Direct Contact**   | Spread by **touching, kissing, sexual contact** with infected person     | AIDS, Skin infections                                    |
| **6. Indirect Contact** | Using **infected objects** like towels, utensils, needles                | Ringworm, Tetanus, Cold                                  |

Types of desese:= infectious and non infectious:
| **S.No.** | **Infectious Diseases**                                           | **Non-Infectious Diseases**                                                   |
| --------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| 1Ô∏è‚É£       | Caused by **pathogens** (bacteria, virus, fungi, protozoa, worms) | Caused by **internal or non-living factors** like genes, nutrition, lifestyle |
| 2Ô∏è‚É£       | **Spread from one person to another**                             | **Do not spread** from one person to another                                  |
| 3Ô∏è‚É£       | Also called **communicable diseases**                             | Also called **non-communicable diseases**                                     |
| 4Ô∏è‚É£       | Can be **epidemic or contagious**                                 | Cannot cause an epidemic                                                      |
| 5Ô∏è‚É£       | **Transmission** through air, water, food, or vectors             | No transmission ‚Äî caused by personal factors                                  |
| 6Ô∏è‚É£       | **Prevented** by maintaining hygiene and vaccination              | **Prevented** by good diet, exercise, and healthy habits                      |
| 7Ô∏è‚É£       | Pathogen can be **identified in the body**                        | No pathogen is present                                                        |
| 8Ô∏è‚É£       | Usually **short-term (acute)**                                    | Often **long-term (chronic)**                                                 |
| 9Ô∏è‚É£       | **Examples:** Malaria, Cholera, Tuberculosis, COVID-19            | **Examples:** Diabetes, Cancer, Heart disease, Scurvy                         |
| üîü        | Treated by **antibiotics or antivirals**                          | Treated by **lifestyle change or long-term therapy**                          |

Conginetal desese:
they are present from birth and they are not transffered:
| **Cause Type**              | **Description**                                                                          | **Examples**                                       |
| --------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| **1. Genetic causes**       | Defects in **genes or chromosomes** passed from parents to child                         | *Down‚Äôs syndrome*, *Hemophilia*, *Color blindness* |
| **2. Environmental causes** | Due to **infection, drugs, radiation, or poor nutrition** of the mother during pregnancy | Heart defects, Cleft lip, Brain disorders          |


| **S.No.** | **Acute Disease**                                  | **Chronic (Non-Acute) Disease**                         |
| --------- | -------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| 1Ô∏è‚É£       | Lasts for a **short duration** (few days or weeks) | Persists for a **long time**, often months or years     |
| 2Ô∏è‚É£       | **Sudden onset** of symptoms                       | **Slow, gradual onset** of symptoms                     |
| 3Ô∏è‚É£       | **Quick recovery** after treatment                 | **Slow or incomplete recovery**                         |
| 4Ô∏è‚É£       | Usually **no long-term effect** on health          | Can cause **permanent damage** or affect body functions |
| 5Ô∏è‚É£       | **Examples:** Common cold, Typhoid, Flu            | **Examples:** Tuberculosis, Diabetes, Cancer, Asthma    |

***Common human desese caued by Infectious agent:
| **S.No.** | **Disease**                    | **Causative Agent**                     | **Mode of Transmission**           | **Organ/Part Affected**    | **Preventive Measures**                         |
| --------- | ------------------------------ | --------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------- | -------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| 1Ô∏è‚É£       | **Tuberculosis (TB)**          | *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* (Bacteria) | Air (droplets from cough/sneeze)   | Lungs                      | BCG vaccine, avoid contact with infected person |
| 2Ô∏è‚É£       | **Cholera**                    | *Vibrio cholerae* (Bacteria)            | Contaminated water/food            | Small intestine            | Drink boiled water, maintain sanitation         |
| 3Ô∏è‚É£       | **Typhoid**                    | *Salmonella typhi* (Bacteria)           | Contaminated food/water            | Intestine                  | Typhoid vaccine, hygiene                        |
| 4Ô∏è‚É£       | **Tetanus**                    | *Clostridium tetani* (Bacteria)         | Wound infection (soil, rust)       | Nervous system             | TT vaccine, wound cleaning                      |
| 5Ô∏è‚É£       | **Common Cold**                | *Rhinovirus* (Virus)                    | Air (droplets)                     | Nose, throat               | Cover mouth/nose, maintain hygiene              |
| 6Ô∏è‚É£       | **Influenza (Flu)**            | *Influenza virus*                       | Air (droplets)                     | Respiratory tract          | Flu vaccine, avoid crowd                        |
| 7Ô∏è‚É£       | **Measles**                    | *Measles virus*                         | Air (droplets)                     | Respiratory system, skin   | Measles vaccine (MMR)                           |
| 8Ô∏è‚É£       | **Polio**                      | *Poliovirus*                            | Contaminated food/water            | Nervous system (paralysis) | Polio drops (oral vaccine)                      |
| 9Ô∏è‚É£       | **Hepatitis A**                | *Hepatitis A virus*                     | Contaminated food/water            | Liver                      | Hepatitis vaccine, hygiene                      |
| üîü        | **Hepatitis B**                | *Hepatitis B virus*                     | Blood transfusion, sexual contact  | Liver                      | HBV vaccine, safe injection practices           |
| 11Ô∏è‚É£      | **Dengue**                     | *Dengue virus*                          | **Aedes mosquito bite**            | Blood (platelets)          | Avoid mosquito bite, clean water storage        |
| 12Ô∏è‚É£      | **Malaria**                    | *Plasmodium* (Protozoa)                 | **Female Anopheles mosquito bite** | Blood, liver               | Mosquito control, nets                          |
| 13Ô∏è‚É£      | **Amoebiasis**                 | *Entamoeba histolytica* (Protozoa)      | Contaminated food/water            | Intestine                  | Hygiene, clean drinking water                   |
| 14Ô∏è‚É£      | **Ringworm**                   | *Fungi (Dermatophytes)*                 | Direct contact, clothes, towels    | Skin                       | Keep skin dry, avoid sharing clothes            |
| 15Ô∏è‚É£      | **Elephantiasis (Filariasis)** | *Wuchereria bancrofti* (Worm)           | **Culex mosquito bite**            | Lymph vessels              | Mosquito control, hygiene                       |

Fungi: it caused the athelete foot:

ü¶† Means of Spread of Infectious Diseases:
üîπ 1. Air-borne Transmission
Spread through tiny droplets released during coughing, sneezing, or talking.
Examples: Common cold, Tuberculosis, Measles, COVID-19.
Prevention: Cover mouth/nose, proper ventilation, mask use.

üîπ 2. Water-borne Transmission
Spread through contaminated water containing pathogens.
Examples: Cholera, Typhoid, Hepatitis A.
Prevention: Drink boiled or purified water, maintain sanitation

üîπ 3. Food-borne Transmission
Spread through contaminated or undercooked food.
Examples: Food poisoning, Amoebiasis.
Prevention: Eat fresh, properly cooked food, wash hands before eating..

üîπ 4. Vector-borne Transmission
Vectors are organisms (usually insects) that carry pathogens from one host to another.
Examples:
Female Anopheles mosquito ‚Üí Malaria
Aedes mosquito ‚Üí Dengue
Culex mosquito ‚Üí Elephantiasis
Prevention: Mosquito control, insect repellents, nets.

üîπ 5. Direct Contact Transmission
Spread by touching, kissing, sexual contact, or contact with wounds/fluids of infected person.
Examples: AIDS, Ringworm, Chickenpox.
Prevention: Avoid direct contact, maintain hygiene, use protection.

üîπ 6. Indirect Contact Transmission
Spread through contaminated objects (towels, utensils, needles).
Examples: Cold, Tetanus.
Prevention: Don‚Äôt share personal items, sterilize medical tools.

*** Common human desese transmitted inside human by insects:
| **S.No.** | **Disease**                    | **Causative Agent**              | **Transmitting Insect (Vector)** | **Mode of Transmission**        | **Preventive Measures**                                     |
| --------- | ------------------------------ | -------------------------------- | -------------------------------- | ------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- |
| 1Ô∏è‚É£       | **Malaria**                    | *Plasmodium* (protozoa)          | **Female Anopheles mosquito**    | Bite of infected mosquito       | Use mosquito nets, insect repellents, remove stagnant water |
| 2Ô∏è‚É£       | **Dengue**                     | *Dengue virus*                   | **Aedes aegypti mosquito**       | Bite of infected mosquito       | Prevent water collection, wear full-sleeved clothes         |
| 3Ô∏è‚É£       | **Chikungunya**                | *Chikungunya virus*              | **Aedes mosquito**               | Bite of infected mosquito       | Avoid mosquito bites, cleanliness around house              |
| 4Ô∏è‚É£       | **Yellow Fever**               | *Yellow fever virus*             | **Aedes mosquito**               | Bite of infected mosquito       | Mosquito control, vaccination                               |
| 5Ô∏è‚É£       | **Elephantiasis (Filariasis)** | *Wuchereria bancrofti* (worm)    | **Culex mosquito**               | Bite of infected mosquito       | Mosquito control, proper sanitation                         |
| 6Ô∏è‚É£       | **Plague**                     | *Yersinia pestis* (bacteria)     | **Rat flea**                     | Bite of infected flea from rats | Kill rats, maintain cleanliness                             |
| 7Ô∏è‚É£       | **Sleeping Sickness**          | *Trypanosoma brucei* (protozoa)  | **Tsetse fly**                   | Bite of infected fly            | Use insect repellents, avoid fly-prone areas                |
| 8Ô∏è‚É£       | **Kala-azar (Leishmaniasis)**  | *Leishmania donovani* (protozoa) | **Sandfly**                      | Bite of infected sandfly        | Insecticide spray, mosquito nets                            |


| **S.No.** | **Symptoms**                                    | **Signs**                                    |
| --------- | ----------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| 1Ô∏è‚É£       | **Changes felt by the patient**                 | **Changes observed by others (doctor)**      |
| 2Ô∏è‚É£       | **Subjective** ‚Äì cannot be measured exactly     | **Objective** ‚Äì can be measured or seen      |
| 3Ô∏è‚É£       | Reported by the **patient**                     | Noticed by the **doctor or observer**        |
| 4Ô∏è‚É£       | Examples: **Headache, nausea, tiredness, pain** | Examples: **Fever, rash, swelling, high BP** |
| 5Ô∏è‚É£       | Help in **early detection** of disease          | Help in **confirmation and diagnosis**       |

üî• Inflammation
üîπ Definition:
Inflammation is the body‚Äôs protective response to injury or infection, in which the affected area becomes red, swollen, hot, and painful.
It helps the body to remove harmful agents (like germs or damaged cells) and start healing.

5 cardinal Signs:
| **No.** | **Sign (Latin Name)** | **Meaning**                        |
| ------- | --------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| 1Ô∏è‚É£     | **Rubor**             | Redness                            |
| 2Ô∏è‚É£     | **Tumor**             | Swelling                           |
| 3Ô∏è‚É£     | **Calor**             | Heat                               |
| 4Ô∏è‚É£     | **Dolor**             | Pain                               |
| 5Ô∏è‚É£     | **Functio laesa**     | Loss of function (in severe cases) |

üîπ Causes:
Infection by bacteria or virus
Physical injury (cut, burn, trauma)
Chemical irritants
Allergic reaction

Purpose / Function:
Destroys or removes pathogens
Clears out dead tissue
Starts repair and healing process

üíä Antibiotics
üîπ Definition:
Antibiotics are chemical substances that kill or inhibit the growth of bacteria and are used to treat bacterial infections.
They are not effective against viruses, fungi, or parasites.

üîπ Discovery:
Alexander Fleming (1928) discovered Penicillin from Penicillium mold.
This was the first widely used antibiotic.

**Types of antibiotics:
| **Type**           | **Action**                                           | **Examples**                  |
| ------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| **Bactericidal**   | **Kill bacteria directly**                           | Penicillin, Streptomycin      |
| **Bacteriostatic** | **Stop bacterial growth** (immune system kills them) | Tetracycline, Chloramphenicol |

**Mechanism of actions:
üîπ Mechanism of Action:
Antibiotics act by targeting bacterial cell structures or functions that are absent in human cells:
Cell wall synthesis inhibition ‚Üí Penicillin, Cephalosporin
Protein synthesis inhibition ‚Üí Tetracycline, Streptomycin
DNA/RNA synthesis inhibition ‚Üí Ciprofloxacin, Rifampicin
Metabolic pathway inhibition ‚Üí Sulfonamides

üîπ Examples of Common Antibiotics:
Penicillin ‚Äì throat infections, wound infections
Streptomycin ‚Äì TB treatment
Tetracycline ‚Äì skin and respiratory infections
Ciprofloxacin ‚Äì urinary tract infections


***Principle of prevention:
üõ°Ô∏è Principles of Prevention of Diseases
Preventing diseases is better than curing them. Prevention reduces suffering, medical costs, and the spread of infections.
üîπ Main Principles:
Maintain Personal Hygiene
Keep body, hands, teeth, and nails clean.
Wash hands before eating and after using the toilet.
Safe Drinking Water & Clean Food
Drink boiled or filtered water.
Eat fresh and properly cooked food.
Avoid contaminated food and water.
Proper Sanitation & Waste Disposal
Dispose of garbage and sewage properly.
Keep surroundings clean to prevent vectors like mosquitoes and flies.
Control of Vectors (Insects & Animals)
Use mosquito nets, insect repellents, and sprays.
Control rodent and fly population to prevent disease spread.
Vaccination / Immunization

**************************************************White Blood cells*********************************
‚ö™ White Blood Cells (WBCs)
üîπ Definition:
White Blood Cells, also called leukocytes, are colorless, nucleated cells in the blood that protect the body against infections and foreign substances.
üîπ Key Features:
Produced in: Bone marrow (primary site)
Present in: Blood and lymph
Normal count: 4000 ‚Äì 11000 per microliter of blood
Life span: Few days to years depending on type
Function: Immunity and defense against pathogens
Protects against many infectious diseases (e.g., Polio, Measles, TB, Hepatitis).
Boosts immunity in children and adults.
Healthy Lifestyle
Eat balanced diet, exercise regularly, and get adequate sleep.
Avoid alcohol, smoking, and junk food.
Early Diagnosis & Treatment
Detect diseases early for timely treatment.
Prevents complications and reduces spread.

‚úÖ In short:
Prevention of diseases includes hygiene, sanitation, vaccination, vector control, safe food & water, and a healthy lifestyle ‚Äî these principles protect both individuals and communities.

*****WBC are classifeid in two groups:******************
1Ô∏è‚É£ Granulocytes (Granular WBCs)
Have visible granules in the cytoplasm.

Short life span (few days).
| **Type**        | **Percentage** | **Function**                                                           | **Examples / Notes**                                |
| --------------- | -------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| **Neutrophils** | 60‚Äì70%         | First line of defense; **phagocytosis of bacteria**                    | Multi-lobed nucleus; respond to bacterial infection |
| **Eosinophils** | 2‚Äì4%           | **Fight parasites** and involved in **allergic reactions**             | Granules stain red with eosin                       |
| **Basophils**   | 0.5‚Äì1%         | Release **histamine & heparin**; cause inflammation & prevent clotting | Granules stain blue; rare in blood                  |

2Ô∏è‚É£ Agranulocytes (Non-Granular WBCs)
No visible granules, larger life span.
| **Type**        | **Percentage** | **Function**                                                                    | **Examples / Notes**                           |
| --------------- | -------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| **Lymphocytes** | 20‚Äì30%         | Produce **antibodies** (**B-cells**) & **cell-mediated immunity** (**T-cells**) | Important for long-term immunity               |
| **Monocytes**   | 3‚Äì8%           | **Phagocytosis**, present antigens to lymphocytes                               | Largest WBC; become **macrophages** in tissues |

üîπ Functions of WBCs (Summary)
Phagocytosis: Engulf and destroy microbes (Neutrophils & Monocytes)
Antibody production: Lymphocytes produce antibodies against pathogens
Allergic response: Eosinophils & Basophils
Inflammation & healing: Basophils release histamine; Monocytes clean damaged tissues
Immunity maintenance: Protect the body from infection

‚úÖ In short:
WBCs are the body‚Äôs defense cells. Granulocytes (Neutrophils, Eosinophils, Basophils) handle immediate defense.
while Agranulocytes (Lymphocytes, Monocytes) provide long-term and adaptive immunity.
